Part 6: Writing and Running Jobs 
Understanding the Scheduler 
ISAAC-NG uses SLURM (Simple Linux Utility for Resource Management) to manage and 
schedule computational jobs. When you submit a job, SLURM places it in a queue and runs it 
when the requested resources become available. You never run computations directly — you 
always submit them through SLURM. 
Partitions and QOS 
SLURM organizes the cluster into logical groups of nodes called partitions. Each partition has a 
set of rules (QOS — Quality of Service) that govern how long a job can run and how many 
resources it can use. The most common ones for new users: 
